    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the advice. i dont think its the sun because they are in a really bright spot. do u think it could be something in the soil though? like maybe they are running out of nutrients? how would i even tell if the soil is the problem?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's possible that your tomato plants are experiencing nutrient deficiencies, which can cause yellowing leaves. To determine if this is the case, you can start by examining the soil pH and nutrient levels. Tomatoes prefer slightly acidic soil with a pH between 6.0 and 6.8. You can test the soil pH using a home testing kit available at most garden centers.\n\nIf the pH is within the ideal range, the next step is to check for nutrient deficiencies. Yellowing leaves can be a sign of nitrogen deficiency, but deficiencies in other nutrients like phosphorus, potassium, or magnesium can also cause similar symptoms. You can purchase a soil test kit to check for these nutrients.\n\nIf you find that your soil is lacking in nutrients, you can address the issue by adding organic matter like compost, manure, or a balanced fertilizer to replenish the nutrients. Be sure to follow the instructions on the fertilizer package for proper application rates.\n\nRemember, it's always a good idea to consult with a local extension service or professional gardener for more specific advice tailored to your region and soil conditions. Good luck with your tomato plants, and don't hesitate to reach out if you have any further questions!",
      "source": "target",
