    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so if it is nitrogen, how quickly does that usually happen? like is it just a slow thing where they run out over time, or does it feel like something is actively stripping the soil bare? i just want to make sure i'm not missing something more urgent.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiencies can develop relatively quickly, especially if your tomato plants are young or if you've recently disturbed the soil, which can temporarily deplete the nitrogen available to your plants. If you've been consistently fertilizing and the plants suddenly show signs of yellowing, it could indicate a recent issue with nitrogen availability.\n\nIt's important to remember that while nitrogen is essential for plant growth, it's not the only nutrient that plants need. A deficiency in one nutrient can sometimes mask or exacerbate a deficiency in another, so it's a good idea to check for multiple nutrient deficiencies if you're experiencing problems.\n\nIf you suspect a nitrogen deficiency, you can address it relatively quickly by applying a balanced, slow-release fertilizer or a nitrogen-rich liquid fertilizer. Be sure to follow the recommended application rates and timing to avoid over-fertilizing, which can harm your plants.\n\nKeep in mind that soil conditions can change over time, and it's important to regularly test your soil and adjust your fertilization practices accordingly. Good luck with your tomato plants, and don't hesitate to reach out if you have any further questions!",
      "source": "target",
